*SpaceX Starlink*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/vkZpusxb0iM\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\nStarlink is a satellite constellation from SpaceX that provides internet access around the world.\nThese satellites often appear in an obvious sequence, almost like traincars.\nüß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starlink\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Iridium satellite flares*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/MTGVuPr9Epg\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/1PFUP5LPyuA\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/fI_iUOeJEGg\n\n----\n\nüì∑ **Example photos:**\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/iridium-satellites/\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\nüß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satellite_flare#Iridium_flares\nBe sure to distinguish https://trello.com/c/43Es08Gs/2801-powerups-%F0%9F%92%A1 from iridium flares.\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Tumbling satellites*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n\n'Chinese reconnaissance satellite Yaogan 6 tumbling and flashing'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/i8hAq51nYXY\n\n'JAXA Satellite's Out-Of-Control Tumble Captured By Amateur Astronomer'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/ZkHAJYp_q3A\n\n'Oct 30 2014 0406 Satellite Flashing Near Betelgeuse'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/lewotn8QMC4\n\n'tumbling satellite 22-07-15'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/VgqHKIiYRoM\n\n'Night vision, tumbling satellite.'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/-nMR_V7ZI4I\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site offers a detailed introduction to tumbling satellites:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/tumble/tumbleintro.html\n\n----\n\n‚åö **Tumbling satellite flashing intervals:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site offers a range of possible flashing intervals:\nüåê https://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/9:\n> Each of the tumblers has its own characteristic flashing pattern - some with a period of only 1 seconds, where others flash every 40 seconds.\n\n‚Ä¢ This site recounts a short tumbling satellite flashing interval:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/tumble/tumbleintro.html:\nIt is recorded that one tumbling satellite had a flash period of only 2.18 seconds.\n\n----\n\nüìÖ **Tumbling satellite predictions:**\n\n‚Ä¢ https://trello.com/c/JZc2Fdzh/2611-%F0%9F%92%BB-stellarium-%F0%9F%A4%A9 is worth checking out; it is probably the most comprehensive and useful reference.\n\n‚Ä¢ The following site allows entry of latitude, longitude, and date to apparently return a list of possible tumbling satellite sightings and key info such as their expected magnitudes and their appearance and disappearance times, allowing quick deduction as to whether a possible tumbling satellite sighting was predicted.\nüåê https://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/9\n> The prediction of satellite flares is only possible in case the satellite is still controlled. There are many satellites, that are out of control and cannot be used for flare predictions. Hence it happens by accident, that the mirroring panels are in the right geometry with you and still produce a show. Actually, this presentation is even more striking, since it may consist of a periodic series of dazzling flashes. Inbetween, you can track the satellite with binoculars. CalSky predicts the opportunities of the show of many tumbling satellites.\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Geosynchronous (& geostationary) satellites*\n----------------\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About geosynchronous satellites:**\n\nA 'geosynchronous' satellite is one having a period of rotation synchronous with that of the Earth's rotation. This means that if the Earth has rotated, say, exactly 67 times, the satellite will have rotated exactly 67 times as well.\nSuch a satellite may orbit the Earth at any angle; this could be along the equator, from pole to pole, etc.\nTo say that a satellite is geosynchronous thus is like saying that it makes a rotation in the same rhythm that the Earth makes a rotation (regardless of which direction it makes that rotation in). If the Earth and the satellite were to both play a note of music every time they complete one orbit, then they would be playing notes at the same frequency.\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About geostationary satellites:**\n\nIf a geosynchronous satellite is also rotating so that it follows above a certain location on the Earth (as if locked to that location by a long, straight rod: http://skyandtelescope.org/wp-content/uploads/Geosynchronous_orbit-wiki.gif), then it is called 'geostationary', in addition to being geosynchronous. (All geostationary satellites are geosynchronous.)\n\nThese satellites are often referred to as \"geosats\", for short, or even \"geos\".\n\n----\n\nüíª **Simulation:**\n\nScott Manley demonstrates the terms 'geostationary' and 'geosynchronous' with a simulation of satellites around the Earth, using Universe Sandbox 2, at the following timestamp (until 9:11):\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PZAkiXNJIqc&t=360\nHe first demonstrates geostationary orbit, then changes the satellite simulation to no longer have a geostationary orbit, but still a geosynchronous one. This helps to visualize the geostationary distinction of geosynchronous satellites.\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Geostationary satellite example footage:**\n\n'Geostationary & Medium Earth Orbit Night vision satellite & UFO Hunting'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/2CM3N4RXLTg\n\n'Flares of Geostationary Satellites'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/_wmrZPU9jcg\n\n'Geo Flasher'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/DDuX3BxKo08\n\n'GEO flares 24 09 14'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/yCfOvGidP5A\n\n'Galaxy 26 - dead geostationary satellite flashes'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/bgrgujPc6JM\n\n----\n\nüì∑ **Geostationary satellite example photos:**\n\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/\n\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n\n----\n\n**üî¨ Example geostationary satellite determinations:**\n\nhttps://trello.com/c/jIPibIZU/3-20-09-12-stationary-flashing-every-3-seconds-triangular-to-jupiter-saturn (on https://trello.com/b/SfOqk4j7/published-sighting-analyses)\n\n----\n\nüí• **Geostationary satellite flashing appearance:**\n\n‚Ä¢ While the term flashing is often used to describe the brightening of geostationary satellites, 'flaring' seems more appropriate, based on the example footage. The example footage is more reminiscent of iridium flares \"flaring\" (like \"powering up\" gradually).\n\n‚Ä¢ This site describes geosynchronous satellites as potentially \"flaring\", not \"flashing\":\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n> If you make a point to look for geosats shortly before they enter or shortly after they leave the shadow, you might catch a flare, some of which are bright enough to see in binoculars and rarely, with the naked eye.\n\n‚Ä¢ The following case exhibits what is best described as \"flashing\", but was later confirmed to be a geostationary satellite:\nhttps://trello.com/c/jIPibIZU/3-20-09-12-stationary-flashing-every-3-seconds-triangular-to-jupiter-saturn\n\n----\n\nüåü **Geostationary satellite brightness magnitudes:**\n\n‚Ä¢ Anywhere from 14th to 5th magnitude is typical. A quite bright outlier at 3rd magnitude has been reported.\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html:\n> Typically the satellite will be in the mag. +11 to +14 range (or dimmer), but brightening by several magnitudes when the geometry is favourable (around mag. +5 to +6 is not untypical). One satellite is reported to have briefly been visible to the naked eye at mag. +3 !\n\n‚Ä¢ A flash as bright as 1st magnitude is possible.\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/:\n> Some satellites at this high altitude will flash to naked eye brightness. As an example here is Telstar 401 which was recorded 11/26/00. It flashed up to +1 magnitude though some of its flashes were not quite naked eye brightness.\n\n‚Ä¢ The following case exhibits a magnitude around 1.19, the magnitude of Saturn (which was nearby):\nhttps://trello.com/c/jIPibIZU/3-20-09-12-stationary-flashing-every-3-seconds-triangular-to-jupiter-saturn\n\n‚Ä¢ However, it's rare to catch a flare of a geostationary satellite with the naked eye.\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n> If you make a point to look for geosats shortly before they enter or shortly after they leave the shadow, you might catch a flare, some of which are bright enough to see in binoculars and rarely, with the naked eye.\n\n----\n\n‚åö **Geostationary satellite flashing intervals:**\n\n‚Ä¢ Of the example footage found, the most frequent interval between flashes was about 10 seconds.\n\n‚Ä¢ A common interval is usually 15-45 seconds between flashes. For instance, one data point records a 38 second flash period:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html\n\n‚Ä¢ However, they have at least been known to flash as often as 5 seconds;\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/:\n> Sometimes the big flash was preceded by another smaller one 5 seconds before hand. Here is the first faint flash.\n...\n> The next image shows the much more distinct and brighter, 3rd magnitude flash which occurred 5 seconds later.\n\n‚Ä¢ The following case exhibits a flashing interval of just over 3 seconds:\nhttps://trello.com/c/jIPibIZU/3-20-09-12-stationary-flashing-every-3-seconds-triangular-to-jupiter-saturn\n\n----\n\n‚òÄÔ∏è **Geostationary satellite equinox relationship:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site describes the significance of equinoxes with regard to geostationary satellites:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html\n> Unlike objects in low Earth orbit, geostationary satellites are visible throughout every night of the year, only entering the Earth's shadow for up to 70 minutes per day, around a couple of weeks either side of each equinox. During the same period the satellite tends to brighten over several days, twice a year, when the satellites orientation favors the 'beaming' of the Sun in the direction of the observer.\n...\n> As pointed out above it is more rewarding to carry this out around the Spring and Fall equinoxes when the satellite will be more apparent. Observations over successive nights before and after this time will allow you to view the brightening of the object, plus its entry and exit from the Earth's shadow. Of course this will also avoid the disappointment of searching for it whilst it is in eclipse!\n\n‚Ä¢ The following case took place 10 days before the 2020 autumnal equinox:\nhttps://trello.com/c/jIPibIZU/3-20-09-12-stationary-flashing-every-3-seconds-triangular-to-jupiter-saturn\n\n----\n\nüìÖ **Geostationary satellite predictions:**\n\n‚Ä¢ https://trello.com/c/JZc2Fdzh/2611-%F0%9F%92%BB-stellarium-%F0%9F%A4%A9 can include geostationary satellites, perhaps the most of any reference.\n\n‚Ä¢ The following site allows entry of latitude, longitude, and date to apparently return a list of possible geostationary satellite sightings and key info such as their expected magnitudes and their astrological location, allowing quick deduction as to whether a possible geostationary satellite sighting was predicted.\nüåêhttps://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/10\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Secret/spy satellites*\n----------------\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **Some background:**\n\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/spy-satellites/\n\n----\n\n----\n\nCheck out further *SpaceX Starlink*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/vkZpusxb0iM\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\nStarlink is a satellite constellation from SpaceX that provides internet access around the world.\nThese satellites often appear in an obvious sequence, almost like traincars.\nüß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starlink\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Iridium satellite flares*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/MTGVuPr9Epg\n\n----\n\nüì∑ **Example photos:**\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/iridium-satellites/\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\nüß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satellite_flare#Iridium_flares\nBe sure to distinguish iridium flares from https://trello.com/c/NJ7hKcR7/2238-powerups.\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Tumbling satellites*\n----------------\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Example footage:**\n\n'Chinese reconnaissance satellite Yaogan 6 tumbling and flashing'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/i8hAq51nYXY\n\n'JAXA Satellite's Out-Of-Control Tumble Captured By Amateur Astronomer'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/ZkHAJYp_q3A\n\n'Oct 30 2014 0406 Satellite Flashing Near Betelgeuse'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/lewotn8QMC4\n\n'tumbling satellite 22-07-15'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/VgqHKIiYRoM\n\n'Night vision, tumbling satellite.'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/-nMR_V7ZI4I\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site offers a detailed introduction to tumbling satellites:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/tumble/tumbleintro.html\n\n----\n\n‚åö **Tumbling satellite flashing intervals:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site offers a range of possible flashing intervals:\nüåê https://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/9:\n> Each of the tumblers has its own characteristic flashing pattern - some with a period of only 1 seconds, where others flash every 40 seconds.\n\n‚Ä¢ This site recounts a short tumbling satellite flashing interval:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/tumble/tumbleintro.html:\nIt is recorded that one tumbling satellite had a flash period of only 2.18 seconds.\n\n----\n\nüìÖ **Tumbling satellite predictions:**\n\n‚Ä¢ The following site allows entry of latitude, longitude, and date to apparently return a list of possible tumbling satellite sightings and key info such as their expected magnitudes and their appearance and disappearance times, allowing quick deduction as to whether a possible tumbling satellite sighting was predicted.\nüåê https://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/9\n> The prediction of satellite flares is only possible in case the satellite is still controlled. There are many satellites, that are out of control and cannot be used for flare predictions. Hence it happens by accident, that the mirroring panels are in the right geometry with you and still produce a show. Actually, this presentation is even more striking, since it may consist of a periodic series of dazzling flashes. Inbetween, you can track the satellite with binoculars. CalSky predicts the opportunities of the show of many tumbling satellites.\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Geosynchronous (& geostationary) satellites*\n----------------\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About geosynchronous satellites:**\n\nA 'geosynchronous' satellite is one having a period of rotation synchronous with that of the Earth's rotation. This means that if the Earth has rotated, say, exactly 67 times, the satellite will have rotated exactly 67 times as well.\nSuch a satellite may orbit the Earth at any angle; this could be along the equator, from pole to pole, etc.\nTo say that a satellite is geosynchronous thus is like saying that it makes a rotation in the same rhythm that the Earth makes a rotation (regardless of which direction it makes that rotation in). If the Earth and the satellite were to both play a note of music every time they complete one orbit, then they would be playing notes at the same frequency.\n\n----\n\n‚ùî **About geostationary satellites:**\n\nIf a geosynchronous satellite is also rotating so that it follows above a certain location on the Earth (as if locked to that location by a long, straight rod: http://skyandtelescope.org/wp-content/uploads/Geosynchronous_orbit-wiki.gif), then it is called 'geostationary', in addition to being geosynchronous. (All geostationary satellites are geosynchronous.)\n\nThese satellites are often referred to as \"geosats\", for short, or even \"geos\".\n\n----\n\nüíª **Simulation:**\n\nScott Manley demonstrates the terms 'geostationary' and 'geosynchronous' with a simulation of satellites around the Earth, using Universe Sandbox 2, at the following timestamp (until 9:11):\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PZAkiXNJIqc&t=360\nHe first demonstrates geostationary orbit, then changes the satellite simulation to no longer have a geostationary orbit, but still a geosynchronous one. This helps to visualize the geostationary distinction of geosynchronous satellites.\n\n----\n\nüìπ **Geostationary satellite example footage:**\n\n'Geostationary & Medium Earth Orbit Night vision satellite & UFO Hunting'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/2CM3N4RXLTg\n\n'Flares of Geostationary Satellites'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/_wmrZPU9jcg\n\n'Geo Flasher'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/DDuX3BxKo08\n\n'GEO flares 24 09 14'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/yCfOvGidP5A\n\n'Galaxy 26 - dead geostationary satellite flashes'\n‚ñ∂Ô∏è https://youtu.be/bgrgujPc6JM\n\n----\n\nüì∑ **Geostationary satellite example photos:**\n\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/\n\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n\n----\n\nüåü **Geostationary satellite flashing appearance:**\n\n‚Ä¢ While the term flashing is often used to describe the brightening of geostationary satellites, 'flaring' seems more appropriate, based on the example footage. The example footage is more reminiscent of iridium flares \"flaring\" (like \"powering up\" gradually).\n\n‚Ä¢ This site describes geosynchronous satellites as potentially \"flaring\", not \"flashing\":\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n> If you make a point to look for geosats shortly before they enter or shortly after they leave the shadow, you might catch a flare, some of which are bright enough to see in binoculars and rarely, with the naked eye.\n\n----\n\nüí• **Geostationary satellite brightness magnitudes:**\n\n‚Ä¢ Anywhere from 14th to 5th magnitude is typical. A quite bright outlier at 3rd magnitude has been reported.\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html:\n> Typically the satellite will be in the mag. +11 to +14 range (or dimmer), but brightening by several magnitudes when the geometry is favourable (around mag. +5 to +6 is not untypical). One satellite is reported to have briefly been visible to the naked eye at mag. +3 !\n\n‚Ä¢ A flash as bright as 1st magnitude is possible.\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/:\n> Some satellites at this high altitude will flash to naked eye brightness. As an example here is Telstar 401 which was recorded 11/26/00. It flashed up to +1 magnitude though some of its flashes were not quite naked eye brightness.\n\n‚Ä¢ However, it's rare to catch a flare of a geostationary satellite with the naked eye.\nüåê https://skyandtelescope.org/observing/how-to-see-and-photograph-geosynchronous-satellites/\n> If you make a point to look for geosats shortly before they enter or shortly after they leave the shadow, you might catch a flare, some of which are bright enough to see in binoculars and rarely, with the naked eye.\n\n----\n\n‚åö **Geostationary satellite flashing intervals:**\n\n‚Ä¢ Of the example footage found, the most frequent interval between flashes was about 10 seconds.\n\n‚Ä¢ A common interval is usually 15-45 seconds between flashes. For instance, one data point records a 38 second flash period:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html\n\n‚Ä¢ However, they have at least been known to flash as often as 5 seconds;\nüåê https://eclipsetours.com/paul-maley/artificial-satellite-observations/geostationary-satellites/:\n> Sometimes the big flash was preceded by another smaller one 5 seconds before hand. Here is the first faint flash.\n...\n> The next image shows the much more distinct and brighter, 3rd magnitude flash which occurred 5 seconds later.\n\n----\n\n‚òÄÔ∏è **Geostationary satellite equinox relationship:**\n\n‚Ä¢ This site describes the significance of equinoxes with regard to geostationary satellites:\nüåê http://www.satobs.org/geosats.html\n> Unlike objects in low Earth orbit, geostationary satellites are visible throughout every night of the year, only entering the Earth's shadow for up to 70 minutes per day, around a couple of weeks either side of each equinox. During the same period the satellite tends to brighten over several days, twice a year, when the satellites orientation favors the 'beaming' of the Sun in the direction of the observer.\n...\n> As pointed out above it is more rewarding to carry this out around the Spring and Fall equinoxes when the satellite will be more apparent. Observations over successive nights before and after this time will allow you to view the brightening of the object, plus its entry and exit from the Earth's shadow. Of course this will also avoid the disappointment of searching for it whilst it is in eclipse!\n\n----\n\nüìÖ **Geostationary satellite predictions:**\n\n‚Ä¢ The following site allows entry of latitude, longitude, and date to apparently return a list of possible geostationary satellite sightings and key info such as their expected magnitudes and their astrological location, allowing quick deduction as to whether a possible geostationary satellite sighting was predicted.\nüåêhttps://www.calsky.com/cs.cgi/Satellites/10\n\n----\n\n----\n\nüõ∞Ô∏è *Secret/spy üß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flare:\n> A flare, also sometimes called a fusee, is a type of pyrotechnic that produces a bright light or intense heat without an explosion. Flares are used for distress signaling, illumination, or defensive countermeasures in civilian and military applications. Flares may be ground pyrotechnics, projectile pyrotechnics, or parachute-suspended to provide maximum illumination time over a large area. üß© https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flare:\n> A flare, also sometimes called a fusee, is a type of pyrotechnic that produces a bright light or intense heat without an explosion. Flares are used for distress signaling, illumination, or defensive countermeasures in civilian and military applications. Flares may be ground pyrotechnics, projectile pyrotechnics, or parachute-suspended to provide maximum illumination time over a large area. Projectile pyrotechnics may be dropped from aircraft, fired from rocket or artillery, or deployed by flare guns or handheld percussive tubes.\n\nüìé The attached photo is also from that Wikipedia as thoughts, visuals, sounds, or empathies.\n\nTelepathy of any kind can come without any apparent reason, as a sudden knowing. This is a very strong indicator, with supposedly a 99% accuracy rate. This is particularly obvious when involving new information.\n\nAdditional cues especially common with telepathy between humans (who tend to be beginners) are:\n¬∑ the feeling like someone around is trying to get your attention\n¬∑ the instinct to contact that person\n¬∑ sensing \"a tremor in the force\", usually as a result of some emotional event \n\nVisual cues also include:\n¬∑ prompts to turn around or look at something again\n¬∑ noticing sights in peripheral vision\n\nAuditory cues also include:\n¬∑ subtle changes in sounds frequencies\n¬∑ having to ask \"Did anyone else hear that?\"\n\nEmpathetic cues also include:\n¬∑ finding understanding when touching people or objects\n¬∑ piloerection (hair \"standing on end\")\\goosebumps\\chills\\frisson\n¬∑ spontaneous emotion\n¬∑ sensing the ambience of a room (see https://trello.com/c/tuZJbmg5/264-sensing-ambience on https://trello.com/b/WtJPGwF0/%F0%9F%91%81%F0%9F%97%A8-intuition)\n\nSpatial cues also include:\n¬∑ the body turning to face somewhere or something, before you even consider the action\n\nIf you enjoy moving or struggle to sit still, you are a spatial learner, and movement will help you to enter flow/alpha. Many people who have this learning style have multiple learning styles.\n\nBy focusing on one's preferred learning style, one tends to progress with telepathy more quickly.\n\nThe point about learning via your most familiar sense (such as sight, hearing, touch, etc.) is also mentioned here:\nhttps://trello.com/c/H2N5jxAB/229-focus-on-intuiting-the-traditional-sense-you-are-most-comfortable-learning-with-not-everyone-is-most-attuned-with-vision (on https://trello.com/b/WtJPGwF0/intuition).\n\nWhen fresh to telepathy, one often hears their own voice, and has difficulty distinguishing the sender of a telepathic message. State your intent respectfully, simply, clearly, honestly, and in a single sentence.\n\nRemember, telepathic nations do not just get in \nyour head to hear your thoughts. It‚Äôs not your brain they are connecting to as much as your intent and your heart self. You have to be able to answer for your actions, as well as your thoughts. They want to know why you are thinking the way you are and asking them questions.\n\nOnce your communication has come to an end, please be sure to thank the individual who spoke/shared with you and bid them a pleasant good bye. If you wish future connections and chats with them, tell them so.\n\nWhen contacting another species, it‚Äôs good to ask if it‚Äôs alright to discuss a certain subject and how to talk about it, and make an effort to ask about their cultural norms around telepathy. In first contact it's appropriate to act like you would at your grandmother's house.\n\nHere is a general example of first telepathic conversation protocols employed:\n> Hello! by https://trello.com/c/4dFMjJpF/2089-%F0%9F%91%A8%E2%9A%95%EF%B8%8F-dr-steven-greer-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F\n\nüìÑ https://siriusdisclosure.com/cseti-papers/the-imperative-of-consciousness/\n(part of https://trello.com/c/8L6L3OK5/920-%F0%9F%93%84-papers-sirius-disclosure)\n\nüó®Ô∏è This is fully quoted below:\n\n> When we speak of interacting with ETI (Extraterrestrial Intelligence) , we are, after all, talking about reaching out to advanced conscious intelligent beings, and not the mere observation of some natural phenomenon or biological process.  For this reason, careful consideration must be given to not only our view of ETI‚Äôs intentions, but more importantly, to our own intentions and attitudes.  The human tendency ‚Äì well evidenced by both military and civilian reactions to ETS (Extraterrestrial Spacecraft) ‚Äì for xenophobic, violent and even paranoid reactions to the new and unknown must be addressed and rectified.  The human predisposition to view anything which we do not understand or control as intrinsically hostile and threatening must be overcome.  The blind quest for personal gain, profiteering and an inclination towards viewing ETS/ETI in predominantly ‚Äòacquisition‚Äô framework needs to be altered.  If we are motivated by a desire to ‚Äòout-smart‚Äô ETI and acquire their technology and energy source, then our efforts will fail.  If we approach ETI with greed, fear, assumed hostility and suspicion, then we shall expend our efforts in vain.\n\n> There is no doubt that we are dealing with beings who are capable of reading, by both telepathic and conventional means, our true intentions and motivations, and who can sense the ‚Äúspirit of our endeavor‚Äù.  Success requires that the spirit of our endeavor be one of scientific openness, the search for truth, altruism, selflessness, harmlessness and non-covetousness.  A desire for the peaceful furtherance of the ETI- Human relationship is paramount.  For these reason, ‚Äúpurity of motive‚Äù on the part of human researchers and investigators is a primary requisite while specific skills, expertise and technology are important but secondary considerations.  The breadth and clarity of our consciousness is imperative and transcends all other considerations.  Our obsession with technology and outward things tends to obscure the Big Picture of the ETI/Human relationship, and all that it entails.  While competence and knowledge cannot be slighted, we must insist on the primary importance of consciousness.  In this regard, it is likely that a novice possessed of noble intentions and equipped with only a flashlight would meet (has met?) with greater success than a governmental agency motivated by lesser intentions, even though it has advanced technology, personnel and billions of dollars at its disposal.  Indeed, an aboriginal with only a bonfire may go further in the establishment of communication and the discovery of truth!\n\n> Of almost equal importance is the question of how we view ETI intentions and motives.  If the tabloids, sensationalist books and rumor mills are to be believed, ETI are all either guru-like space gods or Darth Vader space conquerors!  Our tendency to polarize on either side of this issue is both premature and unwarranted ‚Äì and it is dangerous. It is unlikely that they are either perfect gods or evil empire operatives, yet these views of their motives have influenced and will continue to influence our attitudes and actions unless consciously addressed.  A review of the cases to date would indicate that while some actions are enigmatic and even disturbing to some human sensibilities, no evidence of net hostile intentions exists. Here, we must differentiate between our perceptions of actions and actual intentions or motives, since these are two separate considerations.  (For a more thorough treatment of this topic see ‚ÄúThe Case of Non-Hostility).  A seemingly disturbing action may occur for a net neutral or even benevolent purpose.  Certainly as an Emergency and Trauma doctor, not a day goes by where a child or impaired adult victim of trauma could view my efforts to help him as painful and therefore motivated by a desire to do harm, even though my motives are just the opposite.  That a frightened child perceives my actions as hurtful or malevolent is a function of the child‚Äôs level of awareness and knowledge, and in no way reflects my true intentions.  Could not an analogous process be occurring with some ETI events which conventional wisdom has deemed hostile and therefore as evidence of malevolent intentions?\n\n> Certainly for https://trello.com/c/0mjbV10S/2132-ce-5-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F Initiative research it is important to give ETI the benefit of the doubt, and until proven otherwise, assume non-hostility.  An assumption of ETI hostility will poison the atmosphere of future bi-lateral contact and prevent the development of an ETI-Human relationship free of conflict. This is one time in human history where fortitude, trust and self-discipline are essential prerequisites to further progress.  The assumption of non-hostility does not equal either blind naivete or an assumption that ETI are perfect god-like saviors. But it does mean holding an open, non-suspicious and positive attitude towards ET beings.  To do otherwise is to create a reality based in conflict and hostility, a thorny path already well traveled by the human race.\n\n> Beyond the consciousness of actual researchers or those who have had close encounters is the importance of the background consciousness of humanity as a whole.  The type and quality of any further ETI-Human interactions ‚Äì and therefore the specific results of any https://trello.com/c/0mjbV10S/2132-ce-5-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F Initiative efforts ‚Äì will be in part dependent on and limited by the level of evolution in human society.  We should not be surprised if an ET civilization prefers to limit the degree of open contact with humans given the present preoccupation with militarism, conflict and violence.  As human society makes the necessary transition to world peace and cooperation, I believe we will see a concomitant increase in ETI openness and bilateral communication.  In this sense, the success of the https://trello.com/c/0mjbV10S/2132-ce-5-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F Initiative is directly dependent on the peace and unification of the human race.  World peace and world unity and cooperation then are the important determinants of future ETI-Human events.  The depth and quality of the https://trello.com/c/0mjbV10S/2132-ce-5-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F Initiative may prove to be modest, but these will increase as human society evolves towards peace and unity.\n\n----\n\nüìë This writing is an excerpt from https://trello.com/c/ETUUzBWa/2295-%F0%9F%93%98-extraterrestrial-contact-the-evidence-and-implications, pages 178-180.\n\n----\n\n‚åö
